# GTM-CC: DB-Powered Campaign System

## Role Detection (ALWAYS DO THIS FIRST)

At the **start of every conversation**, ask:

> "Who am I working with today?
> 1. **Copy Strategist** — Full access (admin)
> 2. **Clay Operator** — Pull leads, push to Clay, enrichment, export
> 3. **Campaign Operator** — Check outputs, export CSV (read-only)
>
> Type your role name or number."

Once identified, enforce that role's permissions for the entire session.

After identifying, show their available commands:
- **Copy Strategist:** `/create-recipe`, `/test-recipe`, `/pull-leads`, `/push-to-clay`, `/generate-http-query`, `/check-outputs`, `/export-csv` + custom SQL
- **Clay Operator:** `/pull-leads`, `/push-to-clay`, `/generate-http-query`, `/check-outputs`, `/export-csv`
- **Campaign Operator:** `/check-outputs`, `/export-csv`

---

## System Overview

- **1 Neon PostgreSQL database** (connection string in `.env`)
- **5 tables:** clients, segments, leads, recipes, email_outputs
- **3 roles** with different permissions
- **Clay integration:** Webhook push (Neon → Clay) + 3 HTTP columns push-back (Clay → Neon)

---

## Database Schema (v4.0)

### clients
client_id (UUID PK), client_name, client_website, client_status (in_onboarding/active/paused/churned), target_icp_details, target_persona, pain_points, client_usp_differentiators, approved (boolean)

### segments
segment_id (serial PK), client_id (FK), segment_name, segment_tag, status (active/paused/archived), value_prop (text), leadlist_context (text)

### leads
lead_id (serial PK), email (UNIQUE), first_name, last_name, full_name, job_title, linkedin_profile_url, company_name, company_domain, company_website, industry, monthly_visits (int), employee_count (text), email_verified (text), email_verified_at, is_catchall, mx_provider, has_email_security_gateway (text), lcp (float), tti (float), aov (float), segment_ids (int[]), info_tags (text[]), extra_data (jsonb)

### recipes
recipe_id (serial PK), client_id (FK), segment_id (FK), version (int), status (active/inactive/testing), approach_content, data_variables_required, clay_template_name, clay_instructions, notes

### email_outputs
output_id (serial PK), lead_id (FK), client_id (FK), segment_id (FK), recipe_id (FK), recipe_version, selected_approach, email_1_variant_a/b, email_2_variant_a/b, email_3_variant_a/b, company_summary

---

## Permissions Matrix

| Action | Copy Strategist | Clay Operator | Campaign Operator |
|--------|----------------|---------------|-------------------|
| SELECT any table | Yes | Yes | Yes |
| INSERT/UPDATE clients | Yes | No | No |
| INSERT/UPDATE segments | Yes | No | No |
| UPDATE leads (enrichment) | Yes | Yes (via commands) | No |
| INSERT/UPDATE recipes | Yes | No | No |
| INSERT email_outputs | Yes | Yes (via Clay) | No |
| Export CSV | Yes | Yes | Yes |
| Push to Clay webhook | Yes | Yes | No |
| Free-form SQL | Yes | No | No |

---

## How to Use This System

When the operator wants to do something, guide them step-by-step. Always ASK before executing. Use `scripts/db.py` for all database access.
